This continuous Endurance Run (ER) should be completed at an easy effort with good form. Ensure a thorough warm up prior to starting and slowly ease into the appropriate effort.

If tired or injured then slow down, cut the run short or skip the session entirely.
Endurance Run intensity guide:

Rate of Perceived Exertion: 5-6
Effort/Intensity: Easy - 'Forever' pace
Breathing: Rhythmic, moderate depth, not laboured
Talk test: Comfortable conversation
Heart Rate: Z2 (65-75% MHR or 85-89% LTHR)

Effort is more important than pace.

Workout:

- 15:00 easy Endurance Run warm up
- 6-8 x 00:15 fast strides / 1:30 jog recovery
- 10:00 cooldown at an easy ER effort

Run the stride intervals at a fast but relaxed and controlled effort. Strides are not sprints and you shouldn't be straining. Gently accelerate for the first 5s, hold top speed for 5s and decelerate for 5s.
Stride intensity guide:

RPE: 9-10
Effort: Fast
Breathing: Short and rapid
Talk test: Probably no words
Heart Rate: Z5
Pace: 800 - 1600m

This long run should be completed at an easy effort with good form. Be conscious that your effort might increase with duration so be sure to reduce your pace to keep the effort easy and consistent.

These sessions are an opportunity to practice the fueling and hydration strategy you will use on race day as well as test any gear you will be racing in.

Workout type: Run
Warm up thoroughly prior and begin workout at an easy effort. Find a hill with a 4-8% grade and run fast up whilst remaining relaxed and controlled. Recover by walking back to your starting point and don't start another rep until fully rested or 90s is up.

Hill strides improve mechanical power output, lower leg strength, running economy and reinforce good running form.
